{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646144","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646144"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:26:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:26:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18160"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18160"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.22,0.3,0,0.48]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10874"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80687"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10874"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18160"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65985"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"7378"},{"type":"tags","id":"7383"},{"type":"tags","id":"7385"},{"type":"tags","id":"11414"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25292"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25294"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80687","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80687"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ERotator cuff tears are classified based on their size, which is an important factor in determining the appropriate treatment approach. The size of the tear can influence the prognosis and the choice of surgical or non-surgical management.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is considered a large rotator cuff tear?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Less than 1 cm","1-3 cm","3-5 cm","6-8 cm","Greater than 5 cm"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003E3-5 cm\u003C/strong\u003E tear is classified as a large rotator cuff tear. This classification is important for determining the appropriate treatment strategy and typically indicates a more serious injury that often requires surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe classification of rotator cuff tears by size is as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELess than 1 cm\u003C/strong\u003E represents a small tear that may be amenable to conservative management\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E1-3 cm\u003C/strong\u003E indicates a medium-sized tear\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGreater than 5 cm \u003C/strong\u003E(and therefore \u003Cstrong\u003E6-8cm)\u003C/strong\u003E are considered massive tears, which have a poorer prognosis and may be irreparable\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELarge tears often involve complete detachment of one or more tendons and may be associated with muscle atrophy and fatty infiltration. These factors, along with tear size, influence the surgical approach and likelihood of successful repair.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A large rotator cuff tear is defined as a tear measuring between 3-5 cm.","Rotator cuff tears are classified based on their size, which helps guide treatment decisions.","Understanding the classification of rotator cuff tears is important for diagnosis and management."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Raszewski JA, Black AC, Launico MV, et al. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Hand Compartments. [Updated 2023 Oct 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/books/NBK532942/","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30521257","Rockwood, C. A., Wirth, M. A., \u0026 Fehringer, E. V. (2016). Rockwood and Matsen\u0027s The Shoulder E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","May T, Garmel GM. Rotator Cuff Injury. [Updated 2023 Jun 26]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK547664/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65985"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18160"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65985","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65985"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-22T11:27:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-22T11:28:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10874"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80687"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji"